00:28:01,813 --> 00:28:04,503
But could an entertainment company's inventory of assets be this much?

362
00:28:04,503 --> 00:28:06,133
Normally, it's not that much.

363
00:28:06,133 --> 00:28:10,803
But they say it's due to the two movies People's Entertainment invested in plus success of their products.

364
00:28:10,803 --> 00:28:13,013
- Did you say, "Movies and products"? 
 - Yes.

365
00:28:13,013 --> 00:28:14,283
"Products"?

366
00:28:14,283 --> 00:28:18,283
You know, those items with fan-favorite entertainers' faces on them,

367
00:28:18,283 --> 00:28:21,823
like mugs, t-shirts, and cheering sticks that they buy.

368
00:28:21,823 --> 00:28:23,973
The promotional items.

369
00:28:23,973 --> 00:28:26,353
They already shot the movies,

370
00:28:26,353 --> 00:28:30,723
but due to Covid and competing films at the theater, they're delaying the release date.

371
00:28:30,723 --> 00:28:34,283
In any case, since those movie items were meant to be sold,

372
00:28:34,283 --> 00:28:36,813
they're rightfully part of the company's assets.

373
00:28:37,583 --> 00:28:39,403
But why are you asking?

374
00:28:40,753 --> 00:28:42,793
It's nothing.

375
00:28:42,793 --> 00:28:44,423
Okay.

